objectives.objective: Analyze and apply the understanding of the mechanisms of action and adverse effects of autonomic drugs in the management of autonomic pathology
Discuss quantitative traits in terms of multifactorial inheritance
Analyze how quantitative traits can be controlled by many genes each of which might have minimal contribution to the phenotype
Discuss general concepts of multifactorial disorders
Analyze the threshold model of multifactorial inheritance
Analyze heritability of multifactorial disorders
Discuss methods used to identify genetic or environmental risk factors and contributors for multifactorial disorders
Analyze the normal human karyotype and how it is obtained
Analyze the abnormal human karyotype and define the terms euploidy and aneuploidy. Use disorders and syndromes such as Down, Patau, Edward, Turner, Klinefelter as examples
Analyze meiosis to explain how chromosomal aberrations are formed
Discuss mechanisms that might lead to mosiacism for chromosomal aneuploid conditions
Analyze balanced, unbalanced, reciprocal and Robertsonian translocations, describe how a reciprocal translocation can create a fusion gene
Describe how the Robertsonian translocation can explain Down syndrome. Indicate the risk that a carrier of a Robertsonian translocation has for having a child with Down syndrome
Analyze microdeletion syndromes with the following examples: cri-du-chat, 22q11.2 DS, Wolf_Hirschhorn, Prader-Willi, Angelman
Compare and contrast other chromosomal abnormalities including inversions, ring chromosomes, uniparental disomy and isochromosomes
Analyze cytogenomic tests used for diagnosis of chromosomal aberrations: Karyotype, FISH, Microarray CGH
Define and differentiate between a protooncogene and an oncogene. Summarize the various ways in which oncogenes may transform cells
Compare and contrast tumor suppressor genes, DNA repair genes, and oncogenes

Identify the different classes and functionality of proteins involved in the major cellular proliferative pathway and how mutations in which can result in cancer which includes: Growth factors (hormones), growth factor receptors, cytosolic signal transduction proteins, DNA binding transcription factors

Identify the different types of mutation that would result in the activation of a protooncogene to an oncogene such as point mutation, nonsense mutation, chromosomal translocation, and gene amplification; provide examples for each)

Indicate the specific chromosomal translocation in chronic myeloid leukemia and Burkitt lymphoma. Indicate the genes that are affected by the translocation in each cancer and the molecular basis of tumorigenesis in each example. Interpret a cytogenetic test that detects translocations

Relate the pharmaceutical application of the molecular mechanisms of cancer to the development of anticancer drugs. Include the following specific examples: Herceptin in HER2+ breast cancer, Imaniteb mesylate for Ph+ chronic myeloid leukemia
Compare and contrast the function of the following common oncogenes: Receptor Tyrosine Kinase, Ras, transcription factors
Comprehend the progressive and cumulative nature of cancer at the genetic level using the example of FAP - Compare and contrast FAP to HNPCC (Lynch syndrome)
Compare and contrast the function of the following common tumor suppressor genes: RB, p53, Wilms tumor gene, APC, and NF1
Distinguish the role of tumor suppressor genes including: mutator genes (DNA repair; caretakers); genes involved in cell cycle regulation (gatekeepers); and genes involved in apoptosis regulation
Indicate the genetic basis of Li-Fraumeni syndrome

Analyze the two-hit model where loss of heterozygosity for the action of tumor suppressor genes (inherited mutation vs. sporadic) to understand how the inheritance pattern differs between sporadic and inherited Rb
Interpret familial cancer syndromes and their genetic principles to describe how a predisposition to cancer can be transmitted to offspring use BRCA and APC as examples.
Determine the characteristics of inherited colorectal (familial adenomatous polyposis and hereditary nonpolyposis colon cancer) and breast cancers
Differentiate the clinical presentation of inherited cancers from that of sporadic cancers
Indicate the utility of expression array analysis in cancer
Identify the role of epigenetic changes and microRNA in tumorigenesis
Analyze ways that DNA can be damaged, the cellular mechanisms that are employed in an attempt to fix the damage, and the long and short term consequences of mutation accumulation

Analyze genetic disorders associated with defects of DNA repair including Bloom syndrome, Lynch syndrome (HNPCC), xeroderma pigmentosa, ataxia telangiectasia, BRACA 1/2 hereditary breast and ovarian cancer
Discuss why some areas of the genome are more prone to mutation than other areas; such as repetitive regions, low copy repeats, and 5-methyl cytosine
Discuss the central role of p53 in regulation of cell proliferation, cell survival, and apoptosis
Discuss the role of BAX and BCL-2 in regulating apoptosis: -BAX as pro- apoptotic, -BCL-2 as anti-apoptotic
Indicate how cytochrome c release from mitochondria may initiate apoptosis
Summarize the extrinsic, intrinsic, and perforin pathway of apoptosis with respect to cancer.
